{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17565266","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17565266"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:25:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:25:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17357"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17357","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17357"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.16,0.05,0.14,0.6]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10047"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"88375"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10047","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10047"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17357"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72570"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"808"},{"type":"tags","id":"1115"},{"type":"tags","id":"6627"},{"type":"tags","id":"9419"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23525"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30136"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30137"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"88375","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/88375"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 63-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of a gradually enlarging horn-like growth on the right side of his face. He works as a farmer and spends most of his time outdoors. He has a history of multiple actinic keratoses treated with cryotherapy. He takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a 2 cm keratotic projection with an erythematous base on the right side of his face (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Topical 5-fluorouracil","Curettage and cautery","Reassurance and observation","Cryotherapy","Surgical excision with margins"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a cutaneous horn, which is a clinical description of a  hard conical or cylindrical projection of compacted keratin that can arise from various underlying pathologies ranging from benign such as keratosis, warts or sebaceous molluscum, to malignant conditions such as squamous cell carcinoma or melanoma. The location on a sun-exposed area such as the face or hands in an elderly patient with a history of actinic damage raises concern for underlying malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurgical excision with margins\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management as it allows for complete histological assessment of the base of the lesion. This is crucial as up to 40% of cutaneous horns may have underlying squamous cell carcinoma, particularly in elderly patients with sun-damaged skin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReassurance and observation\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate given the risk of underlying malignancy. The presence of a cutaneous horn warrants investigation and treatment, not observation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECryotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E would be inadequate as it does not allow for histological assessment and may not completely treat an underlying malignancy and may make diagnosis more difficult later. It is more appropriate for confirmed benign lesions or solar keratosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECurettage and cautery\u003C/strong\u003E would also be inappropriate as it does not allow for adequate histological assessment of the margins and base of the lesion, which is essential to rule out malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical 5-fluorouracil\u003C/strong\u003E would not be appropriate without first establishing the histological diagnosis. While it may be useful for treating actinic keratoses, it is not the treatment of choice for cutaneous horns where malignancy needs to be excluded.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cutaneous horns require biopsy to exclude underlying malignancy, particularly in elderly patients.","Squamous cell carcinoma is found in up to 40% of cutaneous horns, especially in sun-exposed areas.","Complete excision with histological margin assessment is the preferred management for cutaneous horns."],"references":["Gil-Mosquera M, Vano-Galvan S, Gomez-Guerra R, Jaen P.  A cutaneous horn on the ear. Australian Family Physician.  2009: 38 (3).  Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/getattachment/9168dd6b-6b95-4019-bd00-0e2570aaa9fc/A-cutaneous-horn-on-the-ear.aspx","Phulari RG, Rathore R, Talegaon TP, Shah A. Cutaneous horn: A mask to underlying malignancy. Journal of Oral Maxillofac Pathology. 2018.  Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5824527/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72570"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17357"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21722"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21722","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21722"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2u8o4SW7D8iv2wsO5mqfzzpbMVWd2D.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2u8o4SW7D8iv2wsO5mqfzzpbMVWd2D.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72570","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/72570"},"attributes":{"crea